''Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego?'' was a commercial blockbuster.<ref name=megahits>{{cite journal | author=Worley, Joyce | title=Mega Hits: The Best of the Best | journal=[[Video Games & Computer Entertainment]] | date=December 1989 | pages=130–132, 137, 138 }}</ref> It was Broderbund's third best-selling Commodore game as of late 1987.<ref name="ferrell198712">{{cite news |last=Ferrell |first=Keith |date=December 1987 |title=The Commodore Games That Live On And On |url=https://archive.org/stream/1987-12-computegazette/Compute_Gazette_Issue_54_1987_Dec#page/n17/mode/2up |work=Compute's Gazette |pages=18–22 |access-date=January 24, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326010059/https://archive.org/stream/1987-12-computegazette/Compute_Gazette_Issue_54_1987_Dec#page/n17/mode/2up |archive-date=March 26, 2016}}</ref> In April 1989, the game was awarded a "Diamond" certification from the [[Software Publishers Association]] for sales above 500,000 units, making it one of the top two [[List of best-selling PC games|best-selling computer games]] in the United States (along with ''[[Karate Champ]]'') up until June 1989.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Petska-Juliussen |first1=Karen |last2=Juliussen |first2=Egil |title=The Computer Industry Almanac 1990 |date=1990 |publisher=Brady |isbn=978-0-13-154122-1 |location=New York |pages=3.10–11 |url=https://archive.org/details/computerindustry00kare/page/n265/mode/2up}}</ref> It went on to achieve sales above 800,000 units by December 1989. At the time, Joyce Worley of ''[[Video Games & Computer Entertainment]]'' called its performance "an incredible accomplishment for any piece of entertainment software and especially remarkable for an educational game."<ref name=megahits /> It had surpassed two million units sold by 1991,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/06/arts/television-the-case-of-the-game-show-ploy.html|title=TELEVISION; The Case of the Game-Show Ploy|last=Rabinovitz|first=Jonathan|date=October 6, 1991|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 25, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043126/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/10/06/arts/television-the-case-of-the-game-show-ploy.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and four million by 1995.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vAsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA91|title=That's Edutainment|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 1, 1995|volume=107|issue=19|page=91|issn=0006-2510|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|access-date=August 8, 2009|archive-date=February 7, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207163131/https://books.google.com/books?id=vAsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA91|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2003, ''Computers and Education'' wrote that ''Carmen Sandiego'' was "by far the best-selling educational software in North America".<ref>{{cite web | access-date=March 5, 2017 | archive-date=March 6, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306034922/https://flexiblelearning.auckland.ac.nz/ela/m3b_b/43/files/EducationVBReadings/computer_assisted_learning_may_not_enhance_education.pdf | url=https://flexiblelearning.auckland.ac.nz/ela/m3b_b/43/files/EducationVBReadings/computer_assisted_learning_may_not_enhance_education.pdf | title=Computer-Assisted Education May Not Enhance Learning | publisher=Robins Lane Press | url-status=live}}</ref>

Roy Wagner reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "The graphics are nice and the manual is well written with a dossier on each thief. The game is good for schools or played as family activity. Everyone is sure to learn something."<ref name="CGW33">{{cite magazine |last=Wagner |first=Roy |title=Commodore Key |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=December 1986 |volume=1 |issue=33 |pages=36}}</ref>

''[[Compute!]]'' called ''Carmen Sandiego'' an example of Broderbund's "attention to detail", and added "that it helps teach research skills and fundamentals of geography as well seems almost too good to be true ... it's entertaining enough to disguise the fact that you might be learning something while you play".<ref name="mccullough198602">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1986-02-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_069_1986_Feb#page/n47/mode/2up | title=Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego? For Apple | work=Compute! | date=February 1986 | access-date=November 8, 2013 | author=McCullough, Karen G. | pages=47 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106235601/http://archive.org/stream/1986-02-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_069_1986_Feb#page/n47/mode/2up | archive-date=January 6, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> The magazine gave it the 1989 Compute! Choice Award for Educational Software, stating that it successfully combined teaching and fun.<ref name="compute198901">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | title=The 189 Compute! Choice Awards | work=Compute! | date=January 1989 | access-date=November 10, 2013 | pages=24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316200847/https://archive.org/stream/1989-01-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_104_1989_Jan#page/n25/mode/2up | archive-date=March 16, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Info (magazine)|Info]]'' gave the Commodore 64 version four-plus stars out of five, describing it as "a really good educational game ... you'll hardly be aware that you've been taught. The graphics and gameplay are nice, too".<ref name="info198701">{{Cite magazine |last1=Dunnington |first1=Benn |last2=Brown |first2=Mark R. |last3=Malcolm |first3=Tom |date=January–February 1987 |title=64/128 Gallery |url=https://archive.org/stream/info-magazine-13/Info_Issue_13_1987_Jan-Feb#page/n13/mode/2up |magazine=Info |pages=14–21 |access-date=October 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709030920/http://archive.org/stream/info-magazine-13/Info_Issue_13_1987_Jan-Feb#page/n13/mode/2up |archive-date=July 9, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>

''[[GamePro]]'' gave the SNES version a positive review. They described it as identical to the earlier PC and Genesis versions, and praised the graphics and the strong [[edutainment]] value.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=ProReviews|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=51|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=October 1993|page=100}}</ref>

